1
00:00:04,682 --> 00:00:08,787
In the Gītā we know, 
so it’s mentioned,

2
00:00:08,789 --> 00:00:11,910
what’s material life 
comparable to

3
00:00:11,910 --> 00:00:14,123
and the suffering 
of material existence—

4
00:00:14,123 --> 00:00:15,930
seasonal changes.

5
00:00:16,227 --> 00:00:19,757
[God | Friend or Enemy]

6
00:00:19,949 --> 00:00:21,952
What is our normal 
response to that?

7
00:00:21,952 --> 00:00:23,633
We have to tolerate it.

8
00:00:23,633 --> 00:00:26,633
Like, we are in this room 
right now, it’s hot.

9
00:00:26,633 --> 00:00:29,302
We have to tolerate it.
Outside it’s hot

10
00:00:29,302 --> 00:00:31,822
or we hear it’s going to rain—
we take an umbrella.

11
00:00:31,822 --> 00:00:34,312
We factor it in, 
it’s part of life.

12
00:00:34,312 --> 00:00:37,271
So He’s telling Arjuna 
in Bhagavad-gītā,

13
00:00:37,271 --> 00:00:41,472
when you’re overwhelmed
by life circumstances,

14
00:00:41,472 --> 00:00:44,942
the karmic situation
that you’ve created,

15
00:00:44,942 --> 00:00:47,858
tāṁs titikṣasva bhārata—
[Bg: 2.14]

16
00:00:47,858 --> 00:00:50,198
tolerate it, Arjuna.

17
00:00:50,198 --> 00:00:54,129
So that just to say here. 
So first He’s making this, says,

18
00:00:54,129 --> 00:00:55,370
and drawing a parallel,

19
00:00:55,370 --> 00:00:59,028
Gītā’s message—
tolerate these circumstances.

20
00:00:59,028 --> 00:01:03,484
The Bhāgavatam saying,
su-samīkṣamāṇo [SB: 10.14.8],

21
00:01:03,484 --> 00:01:07,414
but if you read it more deeply—
not only tolerate it,

22
00:01:07,414 --> 00:01:11,660
you can embrace it 
as something good.

23
00:01:11,660 --> 00:01:14,809
Like, sometimes 
I give the example of jiu-jitsu,

24
00:01:14,809 --> 00:01:17,653
the Japanese jiu-jitsu.

25
00:01:17,653 --> 00:01:23,103
The idea is the opponent is coming 
with full force, and what you do?

26
00:01:23,103 --> 00:01:27,192
You take them and guide them
in a particular direction.

27
00:01:27,192 --> 00:01:34,171
You take advantage 
of that opposition, of the negativity.

28
00:01:34,171 --> 00:01:37,895
So, you think there is a way 
to deal with karmic circumstances

29
00:01:37,895 --> 00:01:39,573
on a deep level reading.

30
00:01:39,573 --> 00:01:42,101
You can see it like that,

31
00:01:42,900 --> 00:01:44,986
and so you’ll think,
“Oh …”

32
00:01:44,986 --> 00:01:48,163
And, excuse me,
in the background—

33
00:01:48,163 --> 00:01:50,773
suhṛdaṁ sarva-bhūtānāṁ
[Bg: 5.29]

34
00:01:50,773 --> 00:01:53,163
and this is where
you get to your part deeper,

35
00:01:53,163 --> 00:01:58,398
if we think, connect this to,
“Well, I’m tolerating.”

36
00:01:58,398 --> 00:02:00,696
But we go deeper 
in Bhagavad-gītā.

37
00:02:00,696 --> 00:02:04,026
He is saying,
suhṛdaṁ sarva-bhūtānāṁ.

38
00:02:04,026 --> 00:02:07,136
He is my friend, who
bhoktāraṁ yajña-tapasāṁ

39
00:02:07,136 --> 00:02:09,546
sarva-loka-maheśvaram—
[Bg: 5.29]

40
00:02:09,546 --> 00:02:13,337
that’s Sanskrit for ‘not a blade of grass 
moves without a will of God’,

41
00:02:13,337 --> 00:02:15,088
it’s for His pleasure.

42
00:02:15,088 --> 00:02:20,178
So we think, “That person, for whom 
everything is meant to please Him,

43
00:02:20,178 --> 00:02:24,918
is He antagonistic towards me 
or friendly to me?”

44
00:02:26,218 --> 00:02:32,268
And really if we think of God 
as being antagonistic to us,

45
00:02:32,268 --> 00:02:38,243
I mean, would He really be like, 
just like some mean guy?

46
00:02:38,243 --> 00:02:42,105
I remember seeing
a bumper sticker in Santa Cruz,

47
00:02:42,105 --> 00:02:45,760
at the back of the corner
said, “Mean people rule”.

48
00:02:45,760 --> 00:02:48,020
[Laughing]

49
00:02:48,210 --> 00:02:50,691
So we think like, so, God,

50
00:02:50,691 --> 00:02:54,051
which we sometimes get 
from a Judeo-Christian saying, like,

51
00:02:54,051 --> 00:03:00,882
“Obey Me, lest I smite thee 
from the face of the Earth,

52
00:03:00,887 --> 00:03:06,123
I’m an angry, jealous God!”—
this kind of stuff.

53
00:03:06,893 --> 00:03:12,583
So, really, He has nothing better to do
than just be mean to people.

54
00:03:12,583 --> 00:03:16,341
It’s so, I mean, 
it would be funny,

55
00:03:16,341 --> 00:03:21,334
I mean, that it’s humorous,
if it wasn’t pathetic.

56
00:03:21,686 --> 00:03:28,312
As Guru Mahārāj told, and I saw 
what he said of visual on YouTube,

57
00:03:28,312 --> 00:03:34,312
where a baby elephant’s trapped 
in the mud, and it’s going to die—

58
00:03:34,312 --> 00:03:39,621
he can’t get out, he didn’t have 
the skills sets for … the wherewithal to get out,

59
00:03:39,621 --> 00:03:41,831
and then you see 
the mother come over

60
00:03:41,831 --> 00:03:46,001
and, like, pull the baby elephant 
out of the mud.

61
00:03:46,001 --> 00:03:49,904
So Guru Majārāj’s just saying,
“If we can witness this,

62
00:03:49,904 --> 00:03:53,248
like an elephant has 
this much love and affection

63
00:03:53,248 --> 00:03:55,608
for their child,

64
00:03:56,268 --> 00:03:59,108
God would be something less 
than that?”

65
00:03:59,108 --> 00:04:03,857
Or more? Or equal, or more?

66
00:04:03,857 --> 00:04:06,223
I mean, it sounds silly.

67
00:04:06,223 --> 00:04:10,543
An elephant is that kind,
but God,

68
00:04:10,543 --> 00:04:14,803
pitāham asya jagato
mātā dhātā pitāmahaḥ
[Bg: 9.17]

69
00:04:14,803 --> 00:04:16,283
who created everyone,

70
00:04:16,283 --> 00:04:19,361
who’s their ultimate mother, 
father, everything,

71
00:04:19,361 --> 00:04:25,340
is less affectionate 
than an elephant, than an animal?

72
00:04:25,790 --> 00:04:27,713
It just can’t be.

73
00:04:27,713 --> 00:04:33,401
So, then, we’re back to that
suhṛdaṁ sarva-bhūtānāṁ—

74
00:04:33,401 --> 00:04:37,981
the person who’s behind 
controlling everything

75
00:04:37,981 --> 00:04:40,374
is friendly to us.

76
00:04:40,374 --> 00:04:44,372
So, these circumstances
that I’m tolerating,

77
00:04:44,372 --> 00:04:47,242
actually, if I look at them
more deeply,

78
00:04:47,242 --> 00:04:50,782
they’re friendly to me, 
it’s in my interest.

79
00:04:50,782 --> 00:04:55,707
Like the … Sometimes you see 
a guardian of a child,

80
00:04:55,707 --> 00:04:59,909
whether their parent
or just a guardian.

81
00:05:00,319 --> 00:05:06,966
From our point of view 
they’re dealing with the child unfairly.

82
00:05:06,966 --> 00:05:10,896
We think they are being cruel, 
mean or unfair.

83
00:05:11,626 --> 00:05:13,454
I mean, sometimes 
that may be true,

84
00:05:13,454 --> 00:05:16,053
but let’s just say 
in this example, it’s not.

85
00:05:16,053 --> 00:05:23,165
And I’ve seen with my own eyes 
like on a tram in San Francisco

86
00:05:23,165 --> 00:05:28,560
some woman dealing with the child,
who was really misbehaving,

87
00:05:28,560 --> 00:05:32,819
but then some people got on
after the misbehaviour,

88
00:05:32,819 --> 00:05:33,967
they didn’t see that,

89
00:05:33,967 --> 00:05:36,857
they just saw the mother, 
like, dealing with the child,

90
00:05:36,857 --> 00:05:40,204
they are like trying 
to correct the mother,

91
00:05:40,204 --> 00:05:44,120
but they didn’t see all the things
that happened before.

92
00:05:44,120 --> 00:05:46,230
So it’s something like that.

93
00:05:46,230 --> 00:05:51,824
And Guru Mahārāj’s saying,
“If we’re in denial—

94
00:05:51,824 --> 00:05:56,694
we deny the responsibility 
for our karmic circumstances:

95
00:05:56,694 --> 00:06:01,206
we’re blaming other people, 
environmental conditions,

96
00:06:01,206 --> 00:06:04,861
historical positioning
whatever it is,

97
00:06:04,861 --> 00:06:07,938
if we’re casting blame 
outward,”

98
00:06:07,938 --> 00:06:11,328
he said, “then you’re going to be
in this world a long time.

99
00:06:11,328 --> 00:06:17,189
Whereas if you take responsibility 
for your karmic circumstances,

100
00:06:17,189 --> 00:06:22,746
and say, ‘I’m alone responsible 
for the positions I find myself in’”,

101
00:06:22,746 --> 00:06:25,297
he said, “then your days here 
are numbered.”

102
00:06:25,297 --> 00:06:29,915
It’s just like the child 
who’s denying any wrong doing,

103
00:06:29,915 --> 00:06:32,525
they get the punishment.

104
00:06:32,525 --> 00:06:36,536
Whereas the child who presents 
themselves to the mother and says,

105
00:06:36,536 --> 00:06:40,285
“I did wrong, 
and I’m really sorry, and …”,

106
00:06:40,285 --> 00:06:45,075
they don’t need to be punished, 
because they’ve acknowledged

107
00:06:45,075 --> 00:06:48,713
their culpability, 
their responsibility.

